  <h2 id="what-the-framework-is-for" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">What the Framework is for</h2>
  <p>
    The LRO framework provides a shared point of reference for designing, developing, and maintaining websites for
    low-resource environments. It establishes common expectations for quality and delivery, so teams can align on
    priorities and make decisions consistently across services.
  </p>
  <p>
    It supports pragmatic, evidence-based work by defining what to optimise for, what an acceptable level of
    performance and accessibility looks like, and how to assess progress. This reduces delivery risk, supports
    ongoing maintenance, and improves outcomes for users in low-resource settings.
  </p>
  <p>The framework is a reference for:</p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Defining what "good" looks like in low-resource conditions (e.g., performance, accessibility, resilience).</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Guiding design and engineering decisions with consistent principles and patterns.</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Supporting maintenance and iteration to ensure improvements are sustainable and measurable.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    It helps teams make trade-offs explicit and evidence-based, so improvements remain reliable without compromising
    clarity, trust, or scientific value.
  </p>

  <h2 id="how-to-use-it" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">How to use it</h2>
  <p>
    Use the LRO framework as a decision-making reference at key stages of delivery. Apply it during planning,
    design, implementation, and quality assurance to guide decisions, set expectations, and validate outcomes.
    This helps cross-functional contributors make consistent choices and maintain improvements over time.
  </p>
  <ol class="vf-list vf-list--ordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Start with the user journey you are supporting (e.g., discover, access, retrieve).</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Identify the likely constraints (bandwidth, latency, device capability, unstable connectivity).</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">
      Apply the relevant guidance:
      <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
        <li class="vf-list__item">Principles (what to prioritise and why)</li>
        <li class="vf-list__item">Patterns (repeatable solutions)</li>
        <li class="vf-list__item">Checks and thresholds (how to validate outcomes)</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">
      Use it during:
      <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
        <li class="vf-list__item">Discovery and planning (scope and priorities)</li>
        <li class="vf-list__item">Design and content decisions (structure, readability, progressive enhancement)</li>
        <li class="vf-list__item">Development and QA (performance budgets, regression checks)</li>
        <li class="vf-list__item">Ongoing maintenance (monitoring and iterative improvement)</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2 id="who-its-for" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Who it's for</h2>
  <p>
    The framework is intended for people responsible for delivering and maintaining web experiences used in
    low-resource settings, including:
  </p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Web developers and engineers</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Designers (UI/UX) and design system contributors</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Content designers, editors, and content owners</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Service leads, product owners, and delivery leads</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">IT and platform teams supporting hosting, deployment, and operations</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="how-it-all-connects" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">How it all connects</h2>
  <p>
    Use the Framework structure and sections to move from intent to execution:
  </p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Start with the outcomes ("What the Framework is for").</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Apply the guidance across delivery ("How to use it").</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Align on roles and ownership ("Who it's for").</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Prove the work with checks and benchmarking ("How to validate").</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Keep it durable through governance and monitoring ("How to sustain and govern it").</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Together, these sections provide a consistent end-to-end approach: define, apply, validate, and sustain.
    The next section focuses on the concrete principles and patterns teams should adopt to deliver those outcomes.
  </p>

